System Design Basics: Service Discovery

Service discovery is a process used in distributed systems, microservices architectures, and service-oriented architectures to automatically detect, locate, and communicate with services or components within the system. It enables applications and services to dynamically discover the available instances of other services, their network locations, and metadata without relying on hardcoded configurations or manual intervention.

â¡ There are two primary approaches to service discovery:
ğ—–ğ—¹ğ—¶ğ—²ğ—»ğ˜-ğ˜€ğ—¶ğ—±ğ—² ğ˜€ğ—²ğ—¿ğ˜ƒğ—¶ğ—°ğ—² ğ—±ğ—¶ğ˜€ğ—°ğ—¼ğ˜ƒğ—²ğ—¿ğ˜†: In this approach, clients (services or applications that consume other services) are responsible for discovering the available service instances, typically by querying a service registry or using a discovery agent. Once the client obtains the necessary information, it can directly communicate with the desired service instance. This approach can offer lower latency and more control over load balancing but increases the complexity on the client side.

ğ—¦ğ—²ğ—¿ğ˜ƒğ—²ğ—¿-ğ˜€ğ—¶ğ—±ğ—² ğ˜€ğ—²ğ—¿ğ˜ƒğ—¶ğ—°ğ—² ğ—±ğ—¶ğ˜€ğ—°ğ—¼ğ˜ƒğ—²ğ—¿ğ˜†: In this approach, a load balancer or a proxy is placed between the clients and services. Clients send requests to the load balancer, which is responsible for discovering the available service instances and forwarding the request to the appropriate instance. This approach offloads discovery and load balancing responsibilities from clients but may introduce additional latency.

